The opening paragraph oi this chapter is beset with very great difficulties, owing to a corruption and lacuna in the text, which scholare have with but indifferent success attempted to solve (see p. 23). The insertion of ‘Sevemm' after Cassium is an evident emendation, for the orator is every· where cited with his full name, with but three exceptions in Quint (VI l, 48 X l, 22 XII, 10, ll), where the context, however, precludes the pomihility oi a misunderstanding. ‘Qui usque’ points unmistakably to a lacuna. Vahlen's and John's restorations give, it must be admitted, every satisfactory sense, and at the same tlme account for the origin of the cor- ruption, hut the emendation oi the former, as John points out, involves the necessity oi referring ‘qui' to the distant antecedent ‘admiratores,'-in my iudgment a fatal objectiou. To obviate this difficulty, lt has been suggested to take ‘huno' as the personal pronoun referring to Cassius Sevems, hut this seems improbable, because the relative ‘qui' clause would in that cese be out of place. John, therefore, substitutes ‘ut’ for ‘qui' which is too bold a change. The possibility of a proper interpretation of ‘reum faciunt* whloh bears all the marks of genuineness, appears to have been lost with the missing words in the lacuna. Michaelis, followed by Peter, Wolll and Andresen, takes ‘quatenus. . . solent’ as a parenthesis, and omits ‘qul usque ad’ and ‘quem reum faciunt,' an emendation withouta shadow 'of intrinsic probability.
